// ============================================================
// TECHNO LESSON 08: Melodic Techno
// ============================================================
// Melodic Techno (sometimes called Melodic Techno/House or
// "Afterhours Techno") is the most emotionally expressive branch
// of the genre. It emerged in the late 2000s–2010s, driven by
// Berlin and Milan's afterhours club culture.
//
// Where traditional techno communicates through rhythm and texture,
// melodic techno layers chord progressions, melodies, and
// atmospheric pads OVER the driving 4/4 beat — creating music
// that is both physically driving and emotionally resonant.
//
// KEY ARTISTS:
//   Tale Of Us — "Astral Me", "Eon" (Afterlife label)
//   Recondite — "Hortus", "Spill"
//   Innellea — "Monolith", "The Traveller"
//   Adam Port (Keinemusik) — melodic house/techno boundary
//   Bicep — "Glue", "Caress"
//   Adriatique, Mathame, Massano
//
// DEFINING CHARACTERISTICS:
//   ✦ Strong, memorable melodic hooks — you can hum this music
//   ✦ Lush, cinematic chord progressions
//   ✦ 4/4 kick — still drives, but less aggressive than hard techno
//   ✦ BPM: 124–134 (slower than dark techno, more room to breathe)
//   ✦ Beautiful, emotional atmosphere
//   ✦ Usually minor key — often Aeolian or Dorian
//   ✦ Pads with slow attack — evolving, swelling textures
//   ✦ Balance: the beat and melody are equally important
//
// MUSIC THEORY — Emotional Chord Progressions:
//   i – VI – III – VII  (Am–F–C–G)    →  hopeful, bittersweet
//   i – VII – VI – VII  (Am–G–F–G)    →  pulsing, circular, trance-like
//   i – iv – i – V      (Am–Dm–Am–E)  →  classical, dramatic
//
// The key to melodic techno's emotion: sustained major 7ths and
// minor 9ths over the chord root. The 7th and 9th add "longing."
// ============================================================

setcpm(65)  // ~130 BPM

// --- EXAMPLE 1: Melodic techno kick — present but not aggressive ---
// Still 4/4, but the kick has a slightly wider, rounder character.
// Room reverb is tiny — just a hint of space.
s("bd*4").gain(0.88).room(0.05)


// --- EXAMPLE 2: Lush chord progression (i – VI – III – VII) ---
// In A minor: Am – F – C – G
// With 7th chords for color: Am7 – Fmaj7 – Cmaj7 – G7
// note("<[a3,c4,e4,g4] [f3,a3,e4,a4] [c4,e4,g4,b4] [g3,b3,d4,f4]>")
//   .sound("sawtooth")
//   .attack(0.5).release(1.2)
//   .lpf(1800)
//   .room(0.6).size(0.7)
//   .gain(0.3)
//   .slow(4)


// --- EXAMPLE 3: Melodic lead (A minor pentatonic) ---
// The melody floats ABOVE the chords. It uses the pentatonic scale
// so it naturally fits every chord change without clashing.
// note("a4 ~ e5 ~ c5 ~ ~ e5 ~ d5 ~ ~ c5 ~ a4 ~")
//   .sound("triangle")
//   .attack(0.02).release(0.35)
//   .delay(0.45).delaytime(0.375).delayfeedback(0.3)
//   .room(0.5)
//   .gain(0.5)
//   .slow(2)


// --- EXAMPLE 4: Bass line that moves with the chords ---
// In melodic techno, the bass follows chord roots — NOT just a
// static note. This is what gives it that "journey" feeling.
// note("<a2 f2 c2 g2>")
//   .sound("sawtooth")
//   .lpf(400)
//   .attack(0.01).decay(0.2).sustain(0.5).release(0.1)
//   .gain(0.65)
//   .slow(2)


// --- EXAMPLE 5: Atmospheric pad layer ---
// A slower, higher pad floats above the main chords.
// It reinforces the harmony but adds shimmer and space.
// note("<[a4,e5] [f4,c5] [c4,g4] [g4,d5]>")
//   .sound("sawtooth")
//   .attack(1.0).release(2.0)
//   .lpf(1200)
//   .room(0.85).size(0.9)
//   .gain(0.18)
//   .pan(0.4)
//   .slow(4)


// --- EXAMPLE 6: Full melodic techno arrangement ---
// This is the complete picture: rhythm + harmony + melody + atmosphere.
// Notice it feels like "music" in a way that minimal techno doesn't.
// stack(
//   // Kick
//   s("bd*4").gain(0.88),
//   // Snare on 2 and 4
//   s("~ ~ sd ~ ~ ~ sd ~").gain(0.72).room(0.1),
//   // Hi-hat — 8th notes, not 16ths (more space, less aggression)
//   s("hh*8").gain(0.28).hpf(7000).pan(0.62),
//   // Open hat accent
//   s("oh/2").gain(0.42).pan(0.58),
//
//   // Chord-following bass
